  "text": "It has been clear for some time that when using classic methods for comparing means, heteroscedasticity (unequal population variances) is a serious concern (e.g., [CITATION_1] . Heteroscedasticity can impact both power and the Type I error probability. The basic reason is that, under general conditions, methods that assume homoscedasticity are using an incorrect estimate of the standard error when in fact there is heteroscedasticity. Indeed, there are concerns regardless of how large the sample size might be. As we consider more and more complicated designs, heteroscedasticity becomes an increasing concern.",
